Formatting and tiying data

First cleaning the names to make sure we have standard names

 # clean colnames
nams <-
  colnames(LPDdata_Feb2016)  %>%
  tolower %>%  # change caps for lower
  str_replace_all("[.]", "_")  # change dots for underscores

colnames(LPDdata_Feb2016) <- nams

Going to the actual data and cleaning there too

LPDdata_Feb2016_cleaned <- LPDdata_Feb2016 %>%
  mutate_all(~str_replace_all(., "/n", "")) %>%  # clean extra lines
  mutate_all(str_trim) # clean any extra spaces

We will now tranform the dataset into tidy data

LPD_tidy <-
  LPDdata_Feb2016_cleaned %>%
  gather(starts_with("x"), key = "year", value = "pop") %>%
  # Get rid of the X in front of years
  mutate(year = as.numeric(str_remove(year, "x")),
        # Create new column with genus and species together
        species_name = paste(genus, species, sep = " "),
        # Clean for / and commas in variables)
        country_list = str_replace_all(country_list, ",", ""),
        biome = str_replace_all(biome, "/", ""))

Now, we will add a few extra columns to the dataset

myLPD <-
  LPD_tidy %>%
  group_by(id) %>%  # each group is a population
  mutate(max_year = max(year), min_year = min(year)) %>%  # create two columns
  mutate(duration = max_year - min_year) %>%
  mutate(scalepop = (pop - min(pop)) / (max(pop) - min(pop))) %>%
  filter(!is.na(scalepop)) %>%
  filter(length(unique(year)) > 5) %>%
  ungroup()

Let’s make a summary statistics for each biome

LPD_biome_summ <- 
  myLPD %>%
  select(biome, duration, sampling_method, units) %>% 
  group_by(biome) %>%  # Group by biome
  summarise(populations = n(),   # Create number of populations
            mean_study_length_years = mean(duration),  # mean study length
            dominant_sampling_method = names(which.max(table(sampling_method))),  # modal sampling method
            dominant_units = names(which.max(table(units)))) %>%  # modal unit type
  ungroup()  ## to always ungroup

Visualising

Before running models, it’s a good idea to visualise our data to explore what kind of distribution we are working with.

Let’s make a nice plot using the custom theme_LPD

(forest_histo <-
   ggplot(LPD_forest, aes(x = scalepop)) +
   geom_histogram(aes(fill = biome),
                  position = "identity", colour = "grey40") +
   geom_vline(aes(xintercept = mean(scalepop)),  # Adding a line for mean abundance
              colour = "darkred", linetype = "dashed", size = 1) +
   scale_fill_manual(values = c("#66CD00", "#53868B")) +
   theme_LPD() +
   labs(title = "a) Data distribution\n") +
   guides(fill = FALSE)) # Hiding the legend - this will be a two plot panel
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

                        # thus we don't need the same legend twice

Next up we can explore for how long populations have been monitored in the two biomes using a density histogram.

(duration_forests <- ggplot(LPD_forest, aes(duration, colour = biome)) +
   # instead of using geom_density we will draw the upper line with
   # stat_density
    stat_density(geom = "line", size = 2, position = "identity") + 
    theme_LPD() +
    scale_colour_manual(values = c("#66CD00", "#53868B")) +
    labs(x = "\nYears", y = "Density\n", title = "b) Monitoring duration\n"))

Now we can arrange the two plots together We’ll use the grid.arrange function from the gridExtra package to combine the two plots in a panel. You can specify the number of columns using ncol = and the number of rows using nrow =.

# Arrange in a panel 
forest_panel <- grid.arrange(forest_histo, duration_forests, ncol = 2)
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Modeling

One specific thing to note is that when you add the lm() function

scalepop_vs_year <- function(df){
  lm(scalepop ~ year, data = df)
}

Calculate population change for each forest population 1785 models in one go! Using pipes and purrr and broom

# check names

# calculate the models
forest_slopes <- LPD_forest %>%
  select(decimal_latitude, decimal_longitude, class, species_name, 
           id, duration, location_of_population, scalepop, year) %>% 
  group_by(decimal_latitude, decimal_longitude, class, species_name, 
           id, duration, location_of_population) %>%
  nest() %>% 
  mutate(fit = purrr::map(data, scalepop_vs_year),  ## call lm function
         tidyfit = purrr::map(fit, broom::tidy)) %>%  ## transform results to tidy data
  unnest(tidyfit) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  filter(term == "year") %>% 
  select(-term) %>% 
  arrange(id)

dim(forest_slopes)
## [1] 1785   11
#[1] 1785   11

Visualising results

Now we can visualise the outputs of all our models and see how they vary based on study duration. We will add density histograms along the margins of the graph which makes for a more informative graph using the ggMarginal() function from the ggExtra package. Note that ggExtra is also an addin in RStudio

# Plotting slope estimates and standard errors for all populations 
# and adding histograms along the margins
(ggplot(forest_slopes, aes(x = duration, y = estimate)) +
   geom_pointrange(aes(ymin = estimate - std.error,
                       ymax = estimate + std.error),
                   alpha = 0.3, size = 0.3) )

With the theme

all_slopes <- ggplot(forest_slopes, aes(x = duration, y = estimate)) +
    geom_pointrange(aes(ymin = estimate - std.error,
                        ymax = estimate + std.error),
                    alpha = 0.3, size = 0.3) +
   geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed") +
   theme_LPD() +
   ylab("Population change\n") +
   xlab("\nDuration (years)")

ggExtra::ggMarginal(
    p = all_slopes,
    type = "density",
    margins = "both",
    size = 5,
    colour = "gray40",
    fill = "gray"
  )
